  "lore.mitemc.book.origins.title": "Origins",
  "lore.mitemc.book.origins.body":  "Avernite saw a player chop a tree in three seconds and decided that was the problem. What you hold is the answer he wrote: not a punishment, but a frame. A frame for caring whether you eat tonight. A frame for missing your tools when they break.\n\nThe earliest builds did not even have flint. You started with nothing and ended with nothing — three hearts the whole way down.",

  "lore.mitemc.book.stone_age.title": "Stone Age",
  "lore.mitemc.book.stone_age.body":  "Sticks fall from leaves because someone has to give you something. Knap two stones together and you have a blade — slow, fragile, alive.\n\nThe first MITE rule: no bare hand carves wood. The first MITE lesson: scarcity is the tutorial.",

  "lore.mitemc.book.forge.title": "The Forge",
  "lore.mitemc.book.forge.body":  "Copper warms easily; iron does too. Silver demands a clean fire. Mithril answers only to lava, and adamantium hates everything that isn't the deep heat of the netherrack pit.\n\nThe order of metals is not chemistry — it is a story about patience.",

  "lore.mitemc.book.deep.title": "The Deep",
  "lore.mitemc.book.deep.body":  "At Y zero the rules tilt. Spiders leap further. Wights drink your hunger. Shadows wait in pitch black for travelers who forgot their torch.\n\nNone of these creatures are punishments. They are reminders that an empty cave is the gentle one.",

  "lore.mitemc.book.mythic.title": "Mythic Age",
  "lore.mitemc.book.mythic.body":  "Adamantium is not a tool material. It is a plateau a player chooses to climb to.\n\nAvernite never finished the mythic content because finishing was never the point — the point was that the mountain existed, that mortals saw it from the valley and sometimes set out toward it.\n\nYou are mortal. You set out.",

  "advancement.mitemc.survival.origins.title": "Origins",
